-- 
Gasoline Futures Advance on Weaker Dollar, Japan Economic Report

-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 
2011-08-15T13:44:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-15/gasoline-futures-advance-on-weaker-dollar-japan-economic-report.html
Gasoline advanced as a weaker dollar
increased the investment appeal of commodities and a report that
 Japan ’s economy shrank less than expected eased concern that
global growth is slowing.  Futures gained as the dollar fell 1.1 percent against the
euro as of 9:36 a.m. in  New York . Japan said today its second-
quarter gross domestic product shrank less than economists
estimated in the second quarter.  “What’s bullish today is the weaker dollar and Japan’s GDP
is a lot stronger than anticipated,” said  Phil Flynn , vice
president of research at PFGBest in Chicago.  Gasoline for September delivery rose 1.48 cents, or 0.5
percent, to $2.837 a gallon at 9:35 a.m. on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange . Futures increased 0.6 percent last week.  Japan’s GDP contracted at an annualized 1.3 percent rate in
the three months ended June 30, marking three consecutive
quarters of declines, the Cabinet office said today in  Tokyo .
The median forecast of 25 economists surveyed by Bloomberg News
was for a 2.5 percent drop.  The Standard & Poor’s GSCI index of 24 raw materials rose
0.8 percent. The S&P’s 500 Index of stocks gained 1.2 percent.  Heating oil for September delivery increased 2.85 cents, or
1 percent, to $2.9322 a gallon on the exchange. Futures sank 1.3
percent last week.  Regular gasoline at the pump, averaged nationwide, fell 0.4
cents to $3.594 a gallon yesterday, according to AAA data.
That’s the lowest level since July 7.  To contact the reporter on this story:
